        "rubricName": "SPIKES — Six-Step Protocol for Delivering Bad News",
        "content": "## SPIKES — six-step protocol for delivering bad news\nEach step scored out of 5. Total 25/30 (0 steps excluded).\n\n## Scorecard\n| Domain | Score |\n| --- | --- |\n| S · Setting up the interview | 3/5 · Good |\n| P · Assessing perception | 5/5 · Excellent |\n| I · Obtaining invitation | 3/5 · Good |\n| K · Giving knowledge | 4/5 · Very good |\n| E · Addressing emotions | 4/5 · Very good |\n| S · Strategy and summary | 4/5 · Very good |\n| **Total** | **25/30** |\n\n### S · Setting up the interview — 3/5 · Good\n- **Evidence:** \"Hi, Sophia. This is Dr. Rissman. I am a pediatric hematology oncology fellow taking care of Ethan.\" Later, when the mother raised family: \"I'm happy to get on the phone with both you and Daniel together.\"\n- **Rationale:** The learner opened with a clear introduction of self and role and stayed verbally engaged and unhurried throughout, pausing when the mother needed a moment. The involvement of a significant other was handled well, though it was patient-initiated rather than proactively invited early. Privacy, seating, and interruption/time management cannot be assessed in this modality, but no aspect harmed the conversation. Solid, but not consistently exemplary enough on the assessable elements to reach the higher anchors.\n- **Recommendations:** Early on, briefly confirm the setting and support — e.g., \"Before we go further, are you somewhere you can talk freely, and is there anyone you'd like me to call to be with you for this?\"\n\n### P · Assessing perception — 5/5 · Excellent\n- **Evidence:** \"before I share with you a bit about what I know now, I would love to hear a bit about what you've been seeing and what you understand.\"\n- **Rationale:** The learner explicitly deferred giving information until eliciting the mother's own account, used a genuinely open-ended prompt, and then tailored the explanation to what she revealed (including acknowledging \"I know what white blood cells are from my work\"). This is the textbook use of perception to guide the disclosure, fully and adaptively accomplished.\n- **Recommendations:** Keep doing this — the \"tell me what you understand first\" move set up the entire conversation. To further sharpen, you could reflect back her stated worry (\"wondering if I missed something\") even more directly before correcting it.\n\n### I · Obtaining invitation — 3/5 · Good\n- **Evidence:** \"what I want to do is take a moment to explain what this means... I wanted to see what questions you have about that.\"\n- **Rationale:** The learner signposted what was coming and checked for questions, which respects the patient's pace. However, there was no explicit invitation asking how much detail she wanted or how she'd prefer to receive it (e.g., all at once vs. gradually). The task was partially accomplished through good signposting rather than a direct invitation, capping it at Good.\n- **Recommendations:** Add an explicit invitation before the diagnosis — e.g., \"Some parents want every detail right away, others want the big picture first — how would you like me to share what we're thinking?\"\n\n### K · Giving knowledge — 4/5 · Very good\n- **Evidence:** \"his blood work showed that all of his blood counts are low, and I know that that's a new term for you\" (warning shot); \"all of these things... are concerning for something called leukemia, which is a cancer of the blood.\"\n- **Rationale:** The learner gave a graded warning, used plain language matched to the mother's vocabulary, chunked the explanation of cell types, checked understanding (\"I wanted to see what questions you have\"), and appropriately conveyed diagnostic uncertainty pending biopsy. Very skillful. It falls short of Excellent because the cell-biology explanation was fairly long before the headline news, and the \"cancer of the blood\" disclosure, while clear, could have been preceded by a slightly firmer warning shot immediately before the word \"leukemia.\"\n- **Recommendations:** Trim the physiology and place a brief warning just before the diagnosis — e.g., \"I'm afraid what we're seeing is serious — the picture is most concerning for leukemia.\"\n\n### E · Addressing emotions — 4/5 · Very good\n- **Evidence:** \"I know you have lots of questions and lots of concerns, and those are completely understandable.\" And to the fear of pain and death: \"Children can absolutely survive this... it is my hope that he lives a long, beautiful, healthy life.\"\n- **Rationale:** The learner validated the mother's distress, allowed her space (\"I need a moment\"), and responded to her fears with reassurance and hope grounded in the real prognosis of pediatric leukemia. This is consistent, warm empathic work. It stops short of Excellent because the emotion was not explicitly named or connected to its source (e.g., her mother's cancer history, her fear of Ethan hurting), and the \"roller coaster... in quotations\" framing, while well-intentioned, slightly minimized the moment when a more direct naming of her fear would have landed better.\n- **Recommendations:** Name and connect the emotion — e.g., \"I can hear how terrified you are, especially with what your mother went through — that fear makes complete sense.\"\n\n### S · Strategy and summary — 4/5 · Very good\n- **Evidence:** \"tomorrow morning... we're gonna take a piece of his bone marrow... once we have those results, then we can talk about Ethan's future.\" And: \"none of this is gonna be done on your own... social workers and our child life supporters, and I will be there.\"\n- **Rationale:** The learner laid out a clear, concrete next-step plan (admission tonight, biopsy tomorrow, then discuss), addressed comfort/sedation concerns, framed realistic hope, and offered wraparound support including help telling Ethan and calling Daniel. The mother's own accurate summary at the end confirms the plan landed. It falls short of Excellent because the learner did not explicitly check her readiness to move into planning before launching into it, and shared decision-making was limited (understandably, given the pre-diagnostic stage).\n- **Recommendations:** Briefly check readiness before pivoting to logistics — e.g., \"Would it help right now to walk through what happens next, or do you need a moment first?\"\n\n## Overall impression\n- **Strengths** — A genuinely strong, humane encounter. The learner led with perception before disclosure (a standout move), used clear plain-language chunking, validated distress repeatedly, offered realistic hope, and proactively removed burdens from the mother (joining the call to Daniel, promising a team to help tell Ethan). The mother's accurate closing summary shows the information was successfully delivered.\n- **Priority gaps** — Two refinements: (1) no explicit invitation asking how much detail she wanted before disclosure, and (2) emotions were validated but not named or tied to their source, and the \"roller coaster in quotations\" phrasing slightly softened a moment that called for direct acknowledgment.\n- **Top action items**\n  1. Add an explicit invitation before disclosing diagnosis (\"How would you like me to share what we're thinking?\").\n  2. Name the specific emotion and link it to its cause before reassuring.\n  3. Place a crisp warning shot immediately before the word \"leukemia,\" and trim the preceding physiology.\n  4. Briefly confirm readiness before pivoting into the logistics/plan.",
