        "gradeId": "d1336396-e3d2-4dc8-8680-a7d7643ddbb5",
        "rubricName": "Pediatric Hematology-Oncology — PROF1: Professional Behavior",
        "content": "## PROF1: Professional Behavior — Level 3 / 5 · Competent\nPediatric Hematology-Oncology milestone · levels 1–5, novice → expert (Dreyfus)\n\n**Assigned level:** 3 · Competent — the highest level fully demonstrated. Levels 4–5 turn largely on behaviors this single encounter could not surface (coaching others, systems/community engagement), so the ceiling is set in part by the simulation, not solely by a learner shortfall.\n\n**Level progression:** Levels 1–3 demonstrated; Level 4 partially demonstrated; Level 5 not assessable in this simulation (no opportunity).\n\n## Evidence by level\n\n### Level 1 · Novice — Demonstrated\nThe learner opened with expected professional behavior — clear self-identification of role, respectful tone, and an information-gathering stance appropriate to breaking bad news, which reflects recognition of the professional behaviors this high-stakes moment demands.\n\"Hi, Sophia. This is Dr. Rissman. I am a pediatric hematology oncology fellow taking care of Ethan. Um, before I share with you a bit about what I know now, I would love to hear a bit about what you've been seeing and what you understand.\"\n\n### Level 2 · Advanced beginner — Demonstrated\nThe learner demonstrated accountability for the patient's care, owning the plan and the ongoing relationship, without notable lapses in professionalism across the encounter.\n\"tomorrow morning, what we're gonna do is we're gonna make him really comfortable and a little bit sleepy, and we're gonna take a piece of his bone marrow...\"\n\n### Level 3 · Competent — Demonstrated\nThe learner maintained professional behavior throughout an emotionally charged, high-complexity disclosure — a possible new leukemia diagnosis in a frightened parent invoking her own mother's cancer death. The learner stayed composed, absorbed distress, relieved guilt, and fully engaged in the patient's care by offering to be personally present through downstream tasks (calling the father, telling the child).\n\"So... Sophia, I wanna share with you that you've done everything right. Um, you brought him in at absolutely the right time.\"\n\"me too, I'm happy to get on the phone with both you and Daniel together so that you don't have to share the news and the burden by yourself.\"\n\n### Level 4 · Proficient — Partially demonstrated\nLevel 4 requires exhibiting a sense of duty to patient care and professional responsibilities beyond the minimum, and recognizing/intervening on triggers for professionalism lapses. The sense of duty is clearly present — the learner volunteered to shoulder emotional labor (joining the family call, being present when the child is told, coordinating social work and child life). However, the \"recognizes triggers and intervenes to prevent lapses in self and others\" element was not observable: there were no other clinicians present to coach, and no situation arose in which the learner had to self-correct or head off a lapse. One judgment call — the \"just a little bit of a roller coaster... just in quotations\" reassurance — arguably overpromises before diagnostic confirmation; a Level 4 clinician might guard against false reassurance as a subtle professionalism/communication risk.\n\"So I want you to know that none of this is gonna be done on your own... You'll have social workers and our child life supporters, and I will be there as well.\"\n\n### Level 5 · Expert — Not assessable in this simulation (no opportunity)\nLevel 5 turns on modeling professional behavior for and coaching others when their behavior falls short, and extending the specialty's role into the community, profession, or specialty at large. A one-on-one family disclosure with no colleagues, trainees, or systems-level context present offered no occasion to demonstrate these behaviors. This does not count against the learner.\n\n## Rationale\nThe learner met every assessable behavior through Level 3. Professionalism held steady across a difficult disclosure: the learner identified their role, elicited the parent's understanding first, relieved her guilt, delivered honest but calibrated news (\"concerning for something called leukemia\"), and committed to accountable follow-through. Engagement in the patient's care was full and personal, not perfunctory — the learner offered to join the call to the father and to be present when the seven-year-old is told, distributing rather than deflecting the burden. That composure and ownership under emotional stress is the defining feature of Level 3.\n\n## Why not the next level\nLevel 4 requires both a demonstrated sense of duty and the ability to recognize triggers for professionalism lapses and intervene to prevent them in oneself and others. The sense of duty is well demonstrated. The lapse-prevention element was only partially observable: no colleague or trainee was present to coach or correct, so the \"in others\" component had no opportunity to appear, and the \"in self\" component was not clearly exercised — indeed the \"roller coaster... you'll be able to get off of very soon\" reassurance, offered before any biopsy confirmation, is a spot where a proficient clinician would more carefully guard against overpromising. Level 5 (coaching others, community/specialty engagement) had no opportunity to surface in a single family encounter.\n\n## Recommendations\n- To reach Level 4, sharpen self-monitoring for the subtle professionalism risk of premature reassurance. Rather than \"just a little bit of a roller coaster that you'll be able to get off of very soon,\" a stronger framing preserves honesty and hope: \"Many children do very well with leukemia — some types are highly curable. I don't yet know Ethan's specific type, so I can't promise you an outcome tonight, but I can promise we will walk through every step together and I'll always tell you the truth about what we learn.\"\n- Continue the excellent habit of distributing emotional burden (offering the joint call, naming the support team) — this is genuine duty to the patient and family.\n- In team settings, look for opportunities to model and, where appropriate, coach colleagues on this same balance of honesty and hope.\n\n## Overall impression\n- **Strengths** — Sustained calm, respectful professionalism through a high-stakes disclosure; elicited the parent's understanding first; actively relieved her guilt; and demonstrated a real sense of duty by volunteering to join the call to the father and to be present when the child is told, backed by naming the multidisciplinary team.\n- **Priority gaps** — The main assessable shortfall was a moment of premature reassurance (\"a roller coaster you'll be able to get off of very soon\") before diagnostic confirmation — a subtle self-monitoring lapse relevant to Level 4. The higher-level behaviors (coaching others, community/specialty engagement) simply had no opportunity to appear in a single family conversation.\n- **Top action items**\n  1. Preserve honesty when offering hope — name curability in general terms while explicitly deferring specifics until the biopsy resolves.\n  2. Keep distributing the emotional and communicative burden across the team, as demonstrated here.\n  3. Seek team-based and systems-level settings where Level 4–5 behaviors (self-correction under pressure, coaching peers, engaging the wider profession) can be developed and observed.",
